x4freetext: K1200 cyclotron.
8B beam produced using 100 and 125 MeV/nucleon beams
of 12C.  Beam magnetically analyzed using a1200
fragment separator.
Beam contaminants included 7Be (5-8 times
more intense than 8B component), 6Li, and 9C.
Statistical uncertainty given.
In addition, there is a 9% systematic uncertainty
due to target thickness and beam intensity.
Data received by email from B.Davids, 26 June
approved by B. Davids, 24 July 2001.

27 mg/cm2 Ag target.
8B particles in beam identified by time-of-
flight.
S800 spectrometer used to detect 7Be fragments
spectrometer comprised of:
. 2 position-sensitive cathode readout drift chambers
to measure position and angles of 7Be fragments,
. a 16 segment ionization chamber to record energy
losses,
. 3 plastic scintillators, the first of which measured
total energies of particles reaching focal plane.
Corrected for overall efficiency of drift chambers,
and angular acceptance of S800 spectrometer.
Reaction corrected.

x4freetext: fig.13
Maximum angle of 8B (p+7Be); exclusive measurement
28 mg/cm2 Pb target.
Protons and 7Be detected in coincidence.
7Be and proton detected in coincidence.
Particle identified by measuring energy loss and
time-of-flight.
Detector system consisted of:
. 4 position-sensitive multi-wire drift chambers
(mwdc) recorded positions of 7Be and p fragments.
. 2 MWDCs used to determine position and angle of
breakup fragments,
. 16 element array of plastic scintillator bars to
measure energy loss.
A stainless steel plate located directly in front of
first mwdc absorbed nearly all of direct beam.
Corrected for detector efficiency and angular and
momentum acceptance.
Reaction corrected.
SD: SF7=5-B-8 was changed to B8 in
REACTION code
